// @check
// @error expected i32, got string | i32
// KNOWN-INCOMPLETE — xfail (ROADMAP A5 flow narrowing). This program is SOUND and
// SHOULD compile, but currently errors. NOT an unsoundness (the compiler is being
// conservative — it rejects a valid program), so it is captured as a "should-run-
// but-errors" xfail rather than a silent compiler fix.
//
// THE GAP: post-guard residual narrowing fires for a *bare sequence* of divergent
// guard-clauses — `if x is string { return … }` then a plain `return x` narrows
// `x` to the complement `i32` (this is what narrowing-null-guard.vl relies on).
// But when the guards are written as an `if`/`else if` CHAIN, the post-chain
// fall-through is NOT narrowed: every arm `return`s, yet below the chain `x` is
// still the full `string | i32`. So `return x` (where `i32` is declared) is
// rejected even though `x` can only be `i32` at that point.
//
// EXPECTED: compiles clean and runs (the else-of-an-exhausted-chain is the
// complement). ACTUAL: `error expected i32, got string | i32`.
//
// TODO(soundness/completeness): make `postGuardNarrowings` see a divergent
// `if/else if` chain as a multi-step subtraction of the discriminated place, the
// same way `conditionsExhaust` already does for the no-`else` exhaustive case.
// When fixed, flip this to `// @run` + `// @log 0` / `// @log 1` and drop @error.
function f(x: string | i32): i32 {
  if x is string { return 0 }
  else if x is string { return 1 }
  return x
}
